[Black "Sidelines: 4. g3"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: The Slav"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-slav/course/5878, variation/239661"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gf5g4][%csl Rc8] The Slav - Introduction The Slav 
Defence - one of Black's most pedigreed and solid options against 1. d4. The 
Slav partly arose from the realisation that the other supporting pawn move, 
...e6, blocked in Black's light-squared bishop. This could turn out to be a 
major problem for Black, which lead black to playing ...c6 often instead. This 
move clearly doesn't share the same downside as ...e6 - the light-squared 
problem bishop is often free to roam outside the pawn chain. It typically makes 
a nuisance of itself on f5 or even g4. Typical Slav Ideas • 1. Black's chief 
idea in the Slav (as opposed to the Queen's Gambit Declined) is to get his 
light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain to f5 or g4. • 2. The problem with 
playing ...Bf5 or ... Bg4 immediately in some variations is that it leaves b7 
undefended. This is usually exploited by White with Qb3. As a result, in the 
mainline - 3. Nf3 followed by 4. Nc3 - Black plays dxc4 so he has a chance to 
develop his bishop to f5. • 3. One of the standard structures in the Slav 
occurs after ... dxc4 - the c6-e6 vs d4 pawn structure. This will be touched on 
more in the Mainline 6. e3 chapter, but I thought it'd be useful to summarise it 
here. Black has less space, but remains very solid. White might want to expand 
further in the centre while Black looks to trade off pieces (since he has less 
space). The structure can also arise from the Scandinavian, so those who play 
that will surely also love this variation. About the Slav The Slav is an opening 
which has been used by the majority of the world's elite players at some point. 
It is certainly a topical choice for players of all levels. If you enjoy solid 
positions that are founded on positional principles, then you should like the 
Slav!} 3. Nf3 ({This is White's most flexible move and if White wants to play 
Nf3 and Nc3 then this is probably the best move order.} 3. Nc3 {is usually 
played with the unique option of following up with 4. e3. 3. Nc3 does, however, 
offer Black another decent option in the form of} 3... dxc4 {- we won't be using 
this option as Black, but I think it's useful to point out the reason for 3. Nf3 
being White's more common move order.}) Nf6 ({The only real move worth 
considering for our repertoire. While} 3... e6 {is playable, I don't see a 
reason to block in the light-squared bishop so early.}) 4. g3 {[%cal Bc8f5] 
About 6-7 years ago, when I was still learning the Catalan as white, I was under 
the impression that it could be played against almost anything - including the 
Slav. Little did I realise how flawed this assumption was. The key difference 
between the Slav and the Closed Catalan (variations where Black refrains from 
taking on c4) is that in the Slav Black's bishop isn't trapped by the pawn on 
e6. This means that the bishop is free to roam, to f5, for example. Now, in the 
Closed Catalan, one of White's main plans is the pawn break e2-e4 (which is 
first prepared by Qc2 and Nbd2). With ...Bf5 inserted, this is clearly not 
possible. As a result, White is forced to look for other plans - these 
alternative ideas are far from convincing though and Black equalises fairly 
easily in this variation.} Bf5 {[%cal Be7e6][%csl Gf5] Getting the bishop out 
before playing ...e6 is obviously best.} 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 {[%cal Gh4f5][%csl 
Rf5]} ({In order to justify 4. g3, white needs to do something other than just 
going through the regular motions.} 6. Bg2 {, O-O and so on simply doesn't cut 
it for White against Black's solid setup.}) dxc4 $1 {[%csl Gc4] Without a knight 
on f3, Black can cause White some problems by grabbing the c4 pawn. Now one of 
the usual manoeuvres to recoup the pawn, Nf3-e5, is no longer possible.} 7. Nxf5 
exf5 8. e3 {[%cal Gf1c4]} Nbd7 $11 {[%cal 
Gf5e4,Bh7h5,Bh5h4,Bg7g6,Bf8g7,Bd7b6,Gb6d5,Gf6e4,Gf6d5][%csl Ge4,Rf3,Rg2,Rh3,Gd5] 
Merely the fact that White has been forced to play g3 and e3 together means that 
White's opening has flopped. This structure is good for Black - his dark-squared 
bishop works nicely in tandem with the pawns on light squares and Black's 
control of the e4 square together with the availability of the semi-open e and d 
files give Black good play.} *

