1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 {The Slav - Introduction The Slav Defence - one of Black's 
most pedigreed and solid options against 1. d4. The Slav partly arose from the 
realisation that the other supporting pawn move, ...e6, blocked in Black's 
light-squared bishop. This could turn out to be a major problem for Black, which 
lead black to playing ...c6 often instead. This move clearly doesn't share the 
same downside as ...e6 - the light-squared problem bishop is often free to roam 
outside the pawn chain. It typically makes a nuisance of itself on f5 or even 
g4. Typical Slav Ideas • 1. Black's chief idea in the Slav (as opposed to the 
Queen's Gambit Declined) is to get his light-squared bishop outside the pawn 
chain to f5 or g4. • 2. The problem with playing ...Bf5 or ... Bg4 immediately 
in some variations is that it leaves b7 undefended. This is usually exploited by 
White with Qb3. As a result, in the mainline - 3. Nf3 followed by 4. Nc3 - Black 
plays dxc4 so he has a chance to develop his bishop to f5. • 3. One of the 
standard structures in the Slav occurs after ... dxc4 - the c6-e6 vs d4 pawn 
structure. This will be touched on more in the Mainline 6. e3 chapter, but I 
thought it'd be useful to summarise it here. Black has less space, but remains 
very solid. White might want to expand further in the centre while Black looks 
to trade off pieces (since he has less space). The structure can also arise from 
the Scandinavian, so those who play that will surely also love this variation. 
About the Slav The Slav is an opening which has been used by the majority of the 
world's elite players at some point. It is certainly a topical choice for 
players of all levels. If you enjoy solid positions that are founded on 
positional principles, then you should like the Slav!} 3. cxd5 {The Exchange 
variation is often treated with disdain as it is supposed to be unambitious and 
drawish. It is favoured by players who would rather not bang their heads against 
the theoretical Slav mainlines and are instead quite satisfied with a small, 
slight advantage for White. For the reasons mentioned above, I play it as White. 
I also think it is quite good as a practical weapon - many Black players think 
it's an automatic draw and are therefore unprepared and taken aback when White 
starts to play for a win. As Black, you must take care not to fall into this 
trap. Treat the exchange slav with some respect and learn the theory well. If 
Black knows some lines here, he should be able to practically equalise here 
after a few moves.} cxd5 4. Nc3 Nf6 {Nf6 vs Nc6} ({Between ...Nf6 and ...Nc6, 
this is the better option.} 4... Nc6 {is actually a bit inaccurate since it 
allows} 5. e4 $1 {which is quite strong for White. Instead, 4... Nf6 steers well 
clear of this by covering e4.}) {The Light-squared Bishop I think GM Simon 
Williams summarised the Exchange Slav nicely when he said the battle revolves 
around Black's light-squared bishop. If he can get it outside the pawn chain 
without a major concession, Black can consider the opening a success. However, 
if White can trap the bishop by provoking an early ...e6, he might get an edge. 
I'd like you to keep this in mind when analysing this variations. At every 
opportunity, Black should look to activate his 'problem piece', the 
light-squared bishop. White's Variations Since White has a whole array of move 
orders to choose from, I've decided to put a focus on setups once again. I've 
divided the Exchange slav lines into Bf4 with a delayed Nf3 and Bf4 with an 
early Nf3.} 5. Bf4 {A flexible move - White intends to delay developing the 
kingside knight.} Nc6 {[%cal Bd1b3,Bc8f5,Gb3d5,Gb3b7][%csl Rb7,Rd5]} ({Note that 
developing the bishop now, instead of Nc6, fails miserably.} 5... Bf5 {is met 
by} 6. Qb3 {with major problems for Black.}) 6. e3 {e3 facilitates White's 
kingside development.} a6 {[%cal Bc8f5,Gb7b5] The position after 6. e3 is a 
major crossroads for black. Let's take a look at black's 4 main options one by 
one:} ({•} 6... e6 {is fairly common, but it blocks in Black's bishop. This is 
something which we'd rather avoid.}) {• 6... Bf5 is a natural move. Black 
intends to meet Qb3 with ...Na5. However, with a crafty manoeuvre White can 
still lock in Black's light-squared bishop: 7. Qb3 Na5 8. Qa4+! Bd7 followed by 
9. Qc2!. Now Black will play ...e6 with his bishop on d7. As previously 
mentioned, we'd rather avoid this.)} ({•} 6... Bg4 {is met in an identical 
way: Qb3-a4-c2. I do quickly want to point out that both ...Bf5 and ...Bg4 are 
very playable, solid variations and would be my second choice. In fact, ...Bf5 
is GM Avrukh's choice in his Slav book - Avrukh's stamp of approval is 
indicative of the fact that it is a great choice as well.}) ({•} 6... a6 {, my 
recommendation. This move is Black's most common and quite possibly best choice. 
Black spends one tempo eliminating the threat of Qb3 once and for all - now it 
is well met with ...b5. Next Black is free to develop his light-squared bishop 
without fear of repercussions. Please note that ...a6 isn't just a prophylactic 
'null' move though - often Black plays it anyway to expand on the queenside with 
...b5.}) 7. Bd3 {[%cal Gd3f5]} Bg4 {[%cal Gg4d1][%csl Rd1] By taking f5 under 
his control, Black is forced to develop his bishop to g4 instead. All is not 
doom and gloom though - Black will often reroute his bishop to g6 via h5 from 
where it can challenge for b1-h7 diagonal.} 8. Nge2 {[%cal Ge2f4,Gf4d3]} ({White 
doesn't want to allow himself to get pinned like after} 8. Nf3 {. Instead, from 
e2 the pin can be broken easily by playing f3 or just moving the queen.}) 
({Playing} 8. f3 {is possible, but it has little independent significance. 
Usually White will play f3 at some point anyway.}) {From e2, the knight has a 
couple of interesting possibilities. One of the most useful is (after Black 
manoeuvres his bishop to g6 and white has moved his bishop from f4) Ne2-f4xd3. 
Once the knight reaches d3, it can hop into either e5 or c5 with interesting 
play.} e6 {[%cal Bf8d6]} 9. O-O Bd6 (9... Be7 {is certainly very playable as 
well, but I feel that the bishop on f4 is slightly better than our one on f8, so 
it makes sense to exchange them.}) 10. f3 {Breaking the pin and kicking our 
bishop back to h5 - the bishop is on its way to g6 anyway.} Bh5 $11 {[%cal 
Bh5g6,Bg6d3,Gb7b5,Gc6a5,Ga8c8,Ga5c4] Play can go in a number of directions from 
here so I recommend taking a look at a couple of games for some inspiration. 
There a couple of general ideas I should point out though: • 1. Black is 
planning ...Bg6 next. The idea is to trade off White's key light-squared bishop. 
• 2. Sometimes White goes for an early Na4-c5 maneouvre. This leads to 
interesting play after ...Bxc5 dxc5. I'd recommend not pushing ...e5 in that 
structure too early, since it could critically weaken d5. • 3. If given the 
chance, Black would love to expand on the queenside. He is all set up for it: at 
some point he'd like to play ...b5, ...Na5, ...Rc8, ...Nc4 and so on.} *

