1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 {The Slav - Introduction The Slav Defence - one of Black's 
most pedigreed and solid options against 1. d4. The Slav partly arose from the 
realisation that the other supporting pawn move, ...e6, blocked in Black's 
light-squared bishop. This could turn out to be a major problem for Black, which 
lead black to playing ...c6 often instead. This move clearly doesn't share the 
same downside as ...e6 - the light-squared problem bishop is often free to roam 
outside the pawn chain. It typically makes a nuisance of itself on f5 or even 
g4. Typical Slav Ideas • 1. Black's chief idea in the Slav (as opposed to the 
Queen's Gambit Declined) is to get his light-squared bishop outside the pawn 
chain to f5 or g4. • 2. The problem with playing ...Bf5 or ... Bg4 immediately 
in some variations is that it leaves b7 undefended. This is usually exploited by 
White with Qb3. As a result, in the mainline - 3. Nf3 followed by 4. Nc3 - Black 
plays dxc4 so he has a chance to develop his bishop to f5. • 3. One of the 
standard structures in the Slav occurs after ... dxc4 - the c6-e6 vs d4 pawn 
structure. This will be touched on more in the Mainline 6. e3 chapter, but I 
thought it'd be useful to summarise it here. Black has less space, but remains 
very solid. White might want to expand further in the centre while Black looks 
to trade off pieces (since he has less space). The structure can also arise from 
the Scandinavian, so those who play that will surely also love this variation. 
About the Slav The Slav is an opening which has been used by the majority of the 
world's elite players at some point. It is certainly a topical choice for 
players of all levels. If you enjoy solid positions that are founded on 
positional principles, then you should like the Slav!} 3. Nc3 {[%cal 
Gc3d5,Gc4d5]} ({While this can be used to reach} 3. Nf3 {followed by 4. Nc3, 
this is typically played with a different idea - 4. e3. White's idea is similar 
to 3. Nf3 followed by 4. e3, but there is a difference: White puts pressure on 
d5 so he is able to meet ...Bf5 strongly with Qb3.}) Nf6 4. e3 {[%cal 
Rc8f5,Gf1c4][%csl Rc1,Rc8]} ({White's play here is directed against Bf5. The 
idea is to meet} 4. e3 4... Bf5 {in the standard way, with} 5. cxd5 {followed by 
6. Qb3 - as in the 3. Nf3 4. Nc3 mainline.}) {The other point it has over the 
mainline is that it neutralises Black's idea of taking on c4, since here White 
can simply recapture with the bishop and have a comfortable position. This does 
make the variation sound great, but its major downside is the fact that it 
blocks in White's dark-squared bishop.} a6 {[%cal Bb7b5,Gc8f5]} ({I've chosen 
this move for a handful of reasons. I think it is interesting to introduce 
readers to this idea, since it features in many Slav variations (including the 
mainline, but that is the Chebanenko Slav).} 4... Bf5 {is, in fact playable, but 
it involves a pawn sacrifice and is rather complicated.}) {I think most users 
would prefer the simplicity of 4... a6. As mentioned above, ...a6 is a standard 
idea in many Slav positions. It might appear weakening (dark squares), but in 
many cases this won't matter. Black's idea is to play ...Bf5 on the next move 
since now cxd5 followed by Qb3 can be met strongly with ...b5!. When playing 
...a6, another important idea just to generally keep in mind is that it's 
possible to protect the b7-pawn with the funny-looking ...Ra7. This is often 
used to meet Qb3.} 5. Qc2 {[%cal Gc2f5][%csl Rc8] White can try use the extra 
tempo Black 'wasted' on ...a6 to prevent ...Bf5 altogether. On the other hand, 
Qc2 isn't such a useful developing move for White either.} e6 $1 {[%cal Bc6c5] A 
nice simple counter. We 'lock' our bishop in, but only temporarily. The idea 
behind e6 is to play the ...c5 break as quickly as possible. After this, the 
lines will open up for our light-squared bishop - after cxd5 ...exd5 - and 
White's queen will find itself a bit misplaced on c2 (vulnerable to ...Nc6-b4 
hops potentially).} 6. Nf3 ({White doesn't have time to create a meaningful bind 
with} 6. c5 {since Black has a chance to break it with} 6... b6 {.}) c5 $1 
{[%cal Bd5c4,Bb7b5,Bc8b7,Gb7h1] Black's big freeing move. The queen on c2 is not 
much better than it would be on d1, so Black's 'lost' tempo (by playing ...c6 
and only then ...c5) is basically irrelevant.} 7. cxd5 {White has little choice 
but to play this since otherwise Black would go for the usual ...dxc4 followed 
by ...b5 plan.} exd5 8. Be2 Nc6 $11 {[%cal Gc8g4] The diagonal for Black's 
light-squared bishop is now open and Black can develop freely.} *

