1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 {The Slav - Introduction The Slav Defence - one of Black's 
most pedigreed and solid options against 1. d4. The Slav partly arose from the 
realisation that the other supporting pawn move, ...e6, blocked in Black's 
light-squared bishop. This could turn out to be a major problem for Black, which 
lead black to playing ...c6 often instead. This move clearly doesn't share the 
same downside as ...e6 - the light-squared problem bishop is often free to roam 
outside the pawn chain. It typically makes a nuisance of itself on f5 or even 
g4. Typical Slav Ideas • 1. Black's chief idea in the Slav (as opposed to the 
Queen's Gambit Declined) is to get his light-squared bishop outside the pawn 
chain to f5 or g4. • 2. The problem with playing ...Bf5 or ... Bg4 immediately 
in some variations is that it leaves b7 undefended. This is usually exploited by 
White with Qb3. As a result, in the mainline - 3. Nf3 followed by 4. Nc3 - Black 
plays dxc4 so he has a chance to develop his bishop to f5. • 3. One of the 
standard structures in the Slav occurs after ... dxc4 - the c6-e6 vs d4 pawn 
structure. This will be touched on more in the Mainline 6. e3 chapter, but I 
thought it'd be useful to summarise it here. Black has less space, but remains 
very solid. White might want to expand further in the centre while Black looks 
to trade off pieces (since he has less space). The structure can also arise from 
the Scandinavian, so those who play that will surely also love this variation. 
About the Slav The Slav is an opening which has been used by the majority of the 
world's elite players at some point. It is certainly a topical choice for 
players of all levels. If you enjoy solid positions that are founded on 
positional principles, then you should like the Slav!} 3. Nc3 ({While this can 
be used to reach} 3. Nf3 {followed by 4. Nc3, this is typically played with a 
different idea - 4. e3. White's idea is similar to 3. Nf3 followed by 4. e3, but 
there is a difference: White puts pressure on d5 so he is able to meet ...Bf5 
strongly with Qb3.}) Nf6 4. e3 ({White's play here is directed against Bf5. The 
idea is to meet} 4. e3 4... Bf5 {in the standard way, with} 5. cxd5 {followed by 
6. Qb3 - as in the 3. Nf3 4. Nc3 mainline.}) {The other point it has over the 
mainline is that it neutralises Black's idea of taking on c4, since here White 
can simply recapture with the bishop and have a comfortable position. This does 
make the variation sound great, but its major downside is the fact that it 
blocks in White's dark-squared bishop.} a6 ({I've chosen this move for a handful 
of reasons. I think it is interesting to introduce readers to this idea, since 
it features in many Slav variations (including the mainline, but that is the 
Chebanenko Slav).} 4... Bf5 {is, in fact playable, but it involves a pawn 
sacrifice and is rather complicated.}) {I think most users would prefer the 
simplicity of 4... a6. As mentioned above, ...a6 is a standard idea in many Slav 
positions. It might appear weakening (dark squares), but in many cases this 
won't matter. Black's idea is to play ...Bf5 on the next move since now cxd5 
followed by Qb3 can be met strongly with ...b5!. When playing ...a6, another 
important idea just to generally keep in mind is that it's possible to protect 
the b7-pawn with the funny-looking ...Ra7. This is often used to meet Qb3.} 5. 
Nf3 Bf5 {[%cal Be7e6] Simple play. Black carries out his plan.} 6. Qb3 {[%cal 
Gb3b7][%csl Rb7] White's most common move.} b5 (6... Ra7 {is another good 
option.}) 7. c5 Nbd7 $11 {[%cal Ga2a4,Ge7e5] An interesting position is on the 
board and both sides have clear strategic goals. Black will want to carry out a 
central ...e5 break, while white will want to crack open the queenside with a4 
at some point.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The Slav"]
[Site "S&S: The Slav"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Nf3 & 4. e3: 10. 0-0-0"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: The Slav"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-slav/course/5878, variation/239663"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 {The Slav - Introduction The Slav Defence - one of Black's 
most pedigreed and solid options against 1. d4. The Slav partly arose from the 
realisation that the other supporting pawn move, ...e6, blocked in Black's 
light-squared bishop. This could turn out to be a major problem for Black, which 
lead black to playing ...c6 often instead. This move clearly doesn't share the 
same downside as ...e6 - the light-squared problem bishop is often free to roam 
outside the pawn chain. It typically makes a nuisance of itself on f5 or even 
g4. Typical Slav Ideas • 1. Black's chief idea in the Slav (as opposed to the 
Queen's Gambit Declined) is to get his light-squared bishop outside the pawn 
chain to f5 or g4. • 2. The problem with playing ...Bf5 or ... Bg4 immediately 
in some variations is that it leaves b7 undefended. This is usually exploited by 
White with Qb3. As a result, in the mainline - 3. Nf3 followed by 4. Nc3 - Black 
plays dxc4 so he has a chance to develop his bishop to f5. • 3. One of the 
standard structures in the Slav occurs after ... dxc4 - the c6-e6 vs d4 pawn 
structure. This will be touched on more in the Mainline 6. e3 chapter, but I 
thought it'd be useful to summarise it here. Black has less space, but remains 
very solid. White might want to expand further in the centre while Black looks 
to trade off pieces (since he has less space). The structure can also arise from 
the Scandinavian, so those who play that will surely also love this variation. 
About the Slav The Slav is an opening which has been used by the majority of the 
world's elite players at some point. It is certainly a topical choice for 
players of all levels. If you enjoy solid positions that are founded on 
positional principles, then you should like the Slav!} 3. Nf3 ({This is White's 
most flexible move and if White wants to play Nf3 and Nc3 then this is probably 
the best move order.} 3. Nc3 {is usually played with the unique option of 
following up with 4. e3. 3. Nc3 does, however, offer Black another decent option 
in the form of} 3... dxc4 {- we won't be using this option as Black, but I think 
it's useful to point out the reason for 3. Nf3 being White's more common move 
order.}) Nf6 ({The only real move worth considering for our repertoire. While} 
3... e6 {is playable, I don't see a reason to block in the light-squared bishop 
so early.}) 4. e3 {Avrukh's recommendation for White against the Slav. It may 
appear safe and unambitious, but White is angling for a small, safe edge. 
White's main plan is to deal with ...Bf5 with Nh4 to try and gain the bishop 
pair. Unlike 3. Nc3 4. e3, this variation doesn't put pressure on d5, but 
instead it allows White to castle faster.} Bf5 {Since 3. Nf3 does nothing to put 
pressure on d5, Qb3 isn't a problem and we are free to develop like this. 
Compare this position to the informational variation after 3. Nf3 4. Nc3.} 5. 
Nc3 {[%cal Gd1b3][%csl Rd5,Rb7] Now Qb3 is threatened.} e6 {[%cal Ge6d5] A 
natural move to solidify d5 and prepare the development of our dark-squared 
bishop. However, it is also the move White was waiting for - we have 'trapped' 
our own bishop on f5.} 6. Nh4 $1 {[%cal Gh4f5][%csl Rf5] The whole idea of this 
variation for White. White has made some concessions to gain the bishop pair, 
which is now unavoidable. Black has a few decent options here:} ({•} 6. Nh4 
6... Bg6 {is simple and good.}) ({•} 6. Nh4 6... Be4 {intends to first provoke 
f3 and only then drop the bishop back to g6.}) ({•} 6. Nh4 6... Bg4 {tries to 
preserve the bishop in a slightly different way, but after} 7. Qb3 {and h3 + g4, 
we are forced to trade off our light bishop anyway.}) Be4 {I think this little 
provocative jab at White, before we are forced to cede the bishop before, is 
best for us.} 7. f3 Bg6 8. Qb3 {[%csl Rb7] White attacks b7 of course. Note that 
White often delays the capture of the bishop on g6 for as long as possible to 
avoid giving Black some extra options with the open h-file and the rook on h8.} 
Qc7 {[%cal Gc7b7]} 9. Bd2 {White gets the bishop off c1 which allows White to 
play Rc1 or sometimes even castle long.} Be7 {This is a large branching point 
where White has tried a plethora of ideas. Black is very solid in all cases, but 
both sides have plenty to play for. I'll offer you 2 sample lines.} 10. O-O-O 
{This is a slightly different plan to the putting the rook on c1.} dxc4 {Black 
hopes to carry out some pawn breaks on the queenside or in the centre now that 
White's king is there.} 11. Qxc4 Nbd7 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gc6c5] A good square for the 
knight where it can support both the ...c5 and ...e5 breaks.} 12. Nxg6 hxg6 
{[%cal Gh8h2,Gc7h2][%csl Rh2]} 13. g3 {Protecting h2.} e5 $11 {[%cal 
Gd7e5,Be8c8][%csl Ge5] Black has achieved his central pawn lever and is now 
doing well.} *

