Compare this position to the informational variation after 3. Nf3 4. Nc3.} 5. 
Nc3 {Now Qb3 is threatened.} e6 {A natural move to solidify d5 and prepare the 
development of our dark-squared bishop. However, it is also the move White was 
waiting for - we have 'trapped' our own bishop on f5.} 6. Nh4 $1 {The whole idea 
of this variation for White. White has made some concessions to gain the bishop 
pair, which is now unavoidable. Black has a few decent options here:} ({•} 6. 
Nh4 6... Bg6 {is simple and good.}) ({•} 6. Nh4 6... Be4 {intends to first 
provoke f3 and only then drop the bishop back to g6.}) ({•} 6. Nh4 6... Bg4 
{tries to preserve the bishop in a slightly different way, but after} 7. Qb3 
{and h3 + g4, we are forced to trade off our light bishop anyway.}) Be4 {I think 
