1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 {The Slav - Introduction The Slav Defence - one of Black's 
most pedigreed and solid options against 1. d4. The Slav partly arose from the 
realisation that the other supporting pawn move, ...e6, blocked in Black's 
light-squared bishop. This could turn out to be a major problem for Black, which 
lead black to playing ...c6 often instead. This move clearly doesn't share the 
same downside as ...e6 - the light-squared problem bishop is often free to roam 
outside the pawn chain. It typically makes a nuisance of itself on f5 or even 
g4. Typical Slav Ideas • 1. Black's chief idea in the Slav (as opposed to the 
Queen's Gambit Declined) is to get his light-squared bishop outside the pawn 
chain to f5 or g4. • 2. The problem with playing ...Bf5 or ... Bg4 immediately 
in some variations is that it leaves b7 undefended. This is usually exploited by 
White with Qb3. As a result, in the mainline - 3. Nf3 followed by 4. Nc3 - Black 
plays dxc4 so he has a chance to develop his bishop to f5. • 3. One of the 
standard structures in the Slav occurs after ... dxc4 - the c6-e6 vs d4 pawn 
structure. This will be touched on more in the Mainline 6. e3 chapter, but I 
thought it'd be useful to summarise it here. Black has less space, but remains 
very solid. White might want to expand further in the centre while Black looks 
to trade off pieces (since he has less space). The structure can also arise from 
the Scandinavian, so those who play that will surely also love this variation. 
About the Slav The Slav is an opening which has been used by the majority of the 
world's elite players at some point. It is certainly a topical choice for 
players of all levels. If you enjoy solid positions that are founded on 
positional principles, then you should like the Slav!} 3. Nf3 ({This is White's 
most flexible move and if White wants to play Nf3 and Nc3 then this is probably 
the best move order.} 3. Nc3 {is usually played with the unique option of 
following up with 4. e3. 3. Nc3 does, however, offer Black another decent option 
in the form of} 3... dxc4 {- we won't be using this option as Black, but I think 
it's useful to point out the reason for 3. Nf3 being White's more common move 
order.}) Nf6 ({The only real move worth considering for our repertoire. While} 
3... e6 {is playable, I don't see a reason to block in the light-squared bishop 
so early.}) 4. Nc3 {A natural move and White's most common choice - this is the 
mainline. 4. Nc3 puts pressure on d5 which means that developing the 
light-squared bishop immediately is impossible for Black.} Bf5 $6 {A 
surprisingly common mistake which I think is very important to point out. As 
previously mentioned, 4. Nc3 attacks d5 to dissuade ...Bf5. The problem with 
...Bf5 is that it leaves b7 unprotected, meaning that Black is vulnerable to Qb3 
which attacks both b7 and d5.} 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Qb3 $14 {[%cal 
Gb3d5,Gb3b7,Gc3d5,Bf3e5,Be2e4][%csl Rb7,Rd5]} ({Now Black has problems. b7 is 
attacked and defending it is very awkward.} 6. Qb3 6... b6 {leaves White with a 
winning attack after} 7. Ne5 {,}) (6. Qb3 6... Qb6 {gives White a great 
endgame}) ({and} 6. Qb3 6... Qd7 {is vulnerable to} 7. Ne5 {.}) ({This leaves} 
6. Qb3 6... Bc8 {- and this move is obviously not something Black would want to 
play.}) *

