[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-slav/course/5878, variation/239673"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 {The Slav - Introduction The Slav Defence - one of Black's 
most pedigreed and solid options against 1. d4. The Slav partly arose from the 
realisation that the other supporting pawn move, ...e6, blocked in Black's 
light-squared bishop. This could turn out to be a major problem for Black, which 
lead black to playing ...c6 often instead. This move clearly doesn't share the 
same downside as ...e6 - the light-squared problem bishop is often free to roam 
outside the pawn chain. It typically makes a nuisance of itself on f5 or even 
g4. Typical Slav Ideas • 1. Black's chief idea in the Slav (as opposed to the 
Queen's Gambit Declined) is to get his light-squared bishop outside the pawn 
chain to f5 or g4. • 2. The problem with playing ...Bf5 or ... Bg4 immediately 
in some variations is that it leaves b7 undefended. This is usually exploited by 
White with Qb3. As a result, in the mainline - 3. Nf3 followed by 4. Nc3 - Black 
plays dxc4 so he has a chance to develop his bishop to f5. • 3. One of the 
standard structures in the Slav occurs after ... dxc4 - the c6-e6 vs d4 pawn 
structure. This will be touched on more in the Mainline 6. e3 chapter, but I 
thought it'd be useful to summarise it here. Black has less space, but remains 
very solid. White might want to expand further in the centre while Black looks 
to trade off pieces (since he has less space). The structure can also arise from 
the Scandinavian, so those who play that will surely also love this variation. 
About the Slav The Slav is an opening which has been used by the majority of the 
world's elite players at some point. It is certainly a topical choice for 
players of all levels. If you enjoy solid positions that are founded on 
positional principles, then you should like the Slav!} 3. Nf3 ({This is White's 
most flexible move and if White wants to play Nf3 and Nc3 then this is probably 
the best move order.} 3. Nc3 {is usually played with the unique option of 
following up with 4. e3. 3. Nc3 does, however, offer Black another decent option 
in the form of} 3... dxc4 {- we won't be using this option as Black, but I think 
it's useful to point out the reason for 3. Nf3 being White's more common move 
order.}) Nf6 ({The only real move worth considering for our repertoire. While} 
3... e6 {is playable, I don't see a reason to block in the light-squared bishop 
so early.}) 4. Nc3 {A natural move and White's most common choice - this is the 
mainline. 4. Nc3 puts pressure on d5 which means that developing the 
light-squared bishop immediately is impossible for Black.} dxc4 {[%cal Bc8f5]} 
({As mentioned in the introduction, one of Black's chief ideas in the Slav is to 
develop his light-squared bishop actively to f5 or g4. The most obvious way to 
do this,} 4... Bf5 $6 {, is dubious due to} 5. cxd5 {exd5 6. Qb3. This is 
demonstrated in the previous informational variation which I recommend you take 
a look at.}) {So, let's take a brief look at the alternatives.} ({•} 4... a6 
{is a funny-looking move which woudn't come naturally to most black players if 
they were confronted with this position for the first time. The idea is clever 
though - Black prepares ...Bf5 since now} 5. Qb3 {can be met with} 5... b5 {. 
White can allow this with e3 or attempt to cramp Black with c5. This ...a6 
variation is known as the Chebanenko Slav and won't be covered in this course.}) 
({•} 4... e6 {seems like a natural choice although this gives up on our aim of 
developing the light-squared bishop actively to f5 or g4. ...e6 is, however, a 
highly respectable choice, known as the Semi-Slav. You might wonder why ...e6 is 
a good move, but chess is a concrete game where variations take preference over 
general considerations. Black reinforces d5 and prepares to develop his 
dark-squared bishop. Although he forfeits the ...Bf5 possibility, he has a new 
plan to get his light-squared bishop into the game - after the natural} 5. e3 {, 
Black will play ...dxc4 at some point followed by ...b5 - and the light-squared 
bishop will become active on b7.} ({The Semi-Slav becomes very sharp and 
concrete after} 5. Bg5 {and won't be covered here.})) ({• The third option, 
and our choice, is} 4... dxc4 {. Black wants to develop his bishop to f5, but, 
as we know, it's not yet possible. Instead, Black first exploits the hanging 
c4-pawn. While White spends time regaining this pawn, Black has a chance to 
develop his light-squared bishop to f5. This is known as the Slav, or the 
Classical Slav (to differentiate it from the other Slav flavours). It will be 
the subject of this course.}) 5. e4 $6 {[%cal Gf1c4] A gambit variation which 
isn't great objectively but one where Black should definitely be aware of what 
to do.} b5 {[%cal Gb5c4,Gb5b4,Gf6e4][%csl Gc4,Re4] White's move would obviously 
be the best choice, were it not for this simple move which seeks to hold on to 
the pawn. White has difficulties finding compensation for the pawn in this 
variation.} 6. e5 Nd5 7. a4 {[%csl Rb5]} e6 $1 (e6 8. axb5 {isn't a threat 
because of the intermediate move} 8... Nxc3 {.}) 8. Be2 Be7 $15 {White doesn't 
have enough for the extra pawn.} *

