following up with 4. e3. 3. Nc3 does, however, offer Black another decent option 
in the form of} 3... dxc4 {- we won't be using this option as Black, but I think 
it's useful to point out the reason for 3. Nf3 being White's more common move 
order.}) Nf6 ({The only real move worth considering for our repertoire. While} 
3... e6 {is playable, I don't see a reason to block in the light-squared bishop 
so early.}) 4. Nc3 {A natural move and White's most common choice - this is the 
mainline. 4. Nc3 puts pressure on d5 which means that developing the 
light-squared bishop immediately is impossible for Black.} dxc4 ({As mentioned 
in the introduction, one of Black's chief ideas in the Slav is to develop his 
light-squared bishop actively to f5 or g4. The most obvious way to do this,} 
4... Bf5 $6 {, is dubious due to} 5. cxd5 {exd5 6. Qb3. This is demonstrated in 
the previous informational variation which I recommend you take a look at.}) 
{So, let's take a brief look at the alternatives.} ({•} 4... a6 {is a 
funny-looking move which woudn't come naturally to most black players if they 
were confronted with this position for the first time. The idea is clever though 
- Black prepares ...Bf5 since now} 5. Qb3 {can be met with} 5... b5 {. White can 
