4... dxc4 {. Black wants to develop his bishop to f5, but, as we know, it's not 
yet possible. Instead, Black first exploits the hanging c4-pawn. While White 
spends time regaining this pawn, Black has a chance to develop his light-squared 
bishop to f5. This is known as the Slav, or the Classical Slav (to differentiate 
it from the other Slav flavours). It will be the subject of this course.}) 5. a4 
{Before White tries to recoup the pawn, he must first eliminate any options 
Black has to support the c4-pawn. 5. a4 prevents ...b5 (which otherwise can give 
White some headaches).} ({Some minor white alternatives like} 5. Ne5 {,}) (5. 
e3) ({and} 5. g3 {sacrifice the pawn for good, but it usually turns out that 
white is short on compensation after} 5... b5 {.}) Bf5 6. e3 {This is White's 
most popular option and one of the two mainlines - 6. Ne5 and 6. e3. At the club 
level, you are more likely to be facing this simple move. White is playing 
normal, albeit slightly unambitious moves. He intends Bxc4 next followed by 
castling. He doesn't attempt to get the ideal e4 and d4 centre immediately - 
like after 6. Ne5 - but rather is planning a slow build-up.} e6 {Of course, we 
can't hold onto the c4-pawn and shouldn't bother trying (there's a reason White 
played a4!). Instead, while White recoups his pawn, we develop.} 7. Bxc4 Bb4 $1 
{Although the bishop can be developed more passively on e7, why should we put it 
there instead of b4? It's important to point out a key feature of this position: 
White's a4 advance severely weakens b4. As a result, our bishop is virtually 
untouchable on b4. Sometimes Black's knight makes use of the square in certain 
variations too. In other cases ...a5 is played to secure the square for Black's 
pieces. Either way, it is important to be aware of this key square as it is 
often used as an outpost for Black's pieces.} 8. O-O O-O ({Both sides castle. At 
this point, white has his first real crossroads: he can go for the critical main 
move of} O-O 9. Qe2 {,}) ({the overambitious} O-O 9. Qb3) ({or the interesting} 
O-O 9. Nh4 {.}) 9. Qe2 {[%cal Be3e4] Now that White is fully developed, he puts 
his centre into motion. Qe2 is played to prepare the idea of expanding in the 
centre with e4. While White's build-up to this point might have appeared 
unambitious, from this point on Black must be on the top of his game to fully 
equalise. Note that this is White's most critical test of Black's setup - and as 
a result, it is also the most popular move White has.} Bg4 $5 {[%cal 
Gg4f3,Gd8d4,Bb8d7,Be6e5][%csl Rd4] 9... Bg4!? Ideas} ({This move is only Black's 
third most common choice and it is hardly a natural move which would normally 
occur to most players. So what's the point in moving the bishop again, you might 
be wondering? White was intending to play 10. e4 on his next move, kicking our 
bishop back while gaining space. 9... Bg4!? could be construed as prophylactic. 
Black pre-empts White's e4 idea and prevents it - now} Bg4 10. e4 {can be met 
by} 10... Bxf3 {followed by ...Qxd4.}) {So now that 10. e4 is ruled out, White's 
most natural response is 10. h3. This is where the second point behind Bg4!? 
comes into play: Black is willing to give up the bishop pair with ...Bxf3!. 
Black reasons that exchanging his 'bad bishop' (based on his pawn structure) for 
White's knight (a crucial piece which controls the important e5-square) is not a 
bad idea. In addition, Black loses no time retreating. By taking White's knight 
on f3, White's grip over e5 is weakened. This means that the position is ripe 
for a well-timed ...e5 break (prepared by ...Nbd7 first, of course). Pawn 
Structure Motifs The e6-c6 pawn structure is a very common one which occurs in 
the Slav, Caro-Kann, Scandinavian and many others. Black's position is 
characterised by these pawns. Black is solid, at the expense of having less 
space. Because of the aforementioned rock-like pawn structure, the effectiveness 
of White's bishop pair (after ...Bxf3) is limited. This means that White would 
like to open the position for his bishops with a well-timed d5 break at some 
point. On the other hand, Black has some decent counterplay of his own. First 
off, if White plays e4, his d4-pawn is exposed. Black can often generate some 
good play down the semi-open d-file as a result. Secondly, Black has two good 
pawn breaks at his disposal: ...c5 and ...e5. Black should keep an eye out for 
this since, when they are implemented successfully, free up Black's position 
(because he has less space). In fact, we will be looking at an example of ...e5 
being successfully implemented in a few moves time. Finally, I'd like to mention 
how many of the ideas in similar structures from openings like the Scandinavian 
(including IM John Bartholomew's repertoire) and the Caro-Kann still apply here. 
There is a slight difference of course (White has his e-pawn here as opposed to 
the c-pawn in the Caro and Scandi), but themes still overlap - for example, it 
is thematic for Black to gladly surrender the light-squared bishop since his 
rock-solid pawn structure compensates for it. Alternatives} ({Finally, I'd just 
like to remind readers that 9... Bg4 is far from Black's only option. In fact, 
the most common move is} 9... Nbd7 {which leads to interesting positions after} 
10. e4 Bg6 {and so on.}) 10. h3 {Kicking Black's bishop around.} Bxf3 {White's 
knight on f3 was a good piece, so surrendering the bishop pair to exchange it is 
a good decision, especially when the alternative is to lose time retreating.} 
11. Qxf3 Nbd7 {[%cal Be6e5] Natural development.} 12. Rd1 {[%cal Gd1d8][%csl 
Rd8]} Rc8 13. e4 {White begins to expand in the centre.} e5 $11 ({Here we see a 
standard implementation of the e5 break. White's central advance is stopped in 
its tracks and Black stakes out his claim to the centre. Importantly, 13... e5 
works well tactically - after} e5 14. dxe5 Nxe5 {White's queen is attacked. Slav 
players would do well to keep the thematic ...e5 break in mind.}) *

