realisation that the other supporting pawn move, ...e6, blocked in Black's 
light-squared bishop. This could turn out to be a major problem for Black, which 
lead black to playing ...c6 often instead. This move clearly doesn't share the 
same downside as ...e6 - the light-squared problem bishop is often free to roam 
outside the pawn chain. It typically makes a nuisance of itself on f5 or even 
g4. Typical Slav Ideas • 1. Black's chief idea in the Slav (as opposed to the 
Queen's Gambit Declined) is to get his light-squared bishop outside the pawn 
chain to f5 or g4. • 2. The problem with playing ...Bf5 or ... Bg4 immediately 
in some variations is that it leaves b7 undefended. This is usually exploited by 
White with Qb3. As a result, in the mainline - 3. Nf3 followed by 4. Nc3 - Black 
plays dxc4 so he has a chance to develop his bishop to f5. • 3. One of the 
standard structures in the Slav occurs after ... dxc4 - the c6-e6 vs d4 pawn 
structure. This will be touched on more in the Mainline 6. e3 chapter, but I 
thought it'd be useful to summarise it here. Black has less space, but remains 
very solid. White might want to expand further in the centre while Black looks 
to trade off pieces (since he has less space). The structure can also arise from 
the Scandinavian, so those who play that will surely also love this variation. 
About the Slav The Slav is an opening which has been used by the majority of the 
world's elite players at some point. It is certainly a topical choice for 
players of all levels. If you enjoy solid positions that are founded on 
positional principles, then you should like the Slav!} 3. Nf3 ({This is White's 
most flexible move and if White wants to play Nf3 and Nc3 then this is probably 
the best move order.} 3. Nc3 {is usually played with the unique option of 
following up with 4. e3. 3. Nc3 does, however, offer Black another decent option 
in the form of} 3... dxc4 {- we won't be using this option as Black, but I think 
it's useful to point out the reason for 3. Nf3 being White's more common move 
order.}) Nf6 ({The only real move worth considering for our repertoire. While} 
3... e6 {is playable, I don't see a reason to block in the light-squared bishop 
so early.}) 4. Nc3 {A natural move and White's most common choice - this is the 
mainline. 4. Nc3 puts pressure on d5 which means that developing the 
light-squared bishop immediately is impossible for Black.} dxc4 ({As mentioned 
in the introduction, one of Black's chief ideas in the Slav is to develop his 
light-squared bishop actively to f5 or g4. The most obvious way to do this,} 
4... Bf5 $6 {, is dubious due to} 5. cxd5 {exd5 6. Qb3. This is demonstrated in 
the previous informational variation which I recommend you take a look at.}) 
{So, let's take a brief look at the alternatives.} ({•} 4... a6 {is a 
funny-looking move which woudn't come naturally to most black players if they 
were confronted with this position for the first time. The idea is clever though 
- Black prepares ...Bf5 since now} 5. Qb3 {can be met with} 5... b5 {. White can 
allow this with e3 or attempt to cramp Black with c5. This ...a6 variation is 
known as the Chebanenko Slav and won't be covered in this course.}) ({•} 4... 
e6 {seems like a natural choice although this gives up on our aim of developing 
the light-squared bishop actively to f5 or g4. ...e6 is, however, a highly 
respectable choice, known as the Semi-Slav. You might wonder why ...e6 is a good 
move, but chess is a concrete game where variations take preference over general 
considerations. Black reinforces d5 and prepares to develop his dark-squared 
bishop. Although he forfeits the ...Bf5 possibility, he has a new plan to get 
his light-squared bishop into the game - after the natural} 5. e3 {, Black will 
play ...dxc4 at some point followed by ...b5 - and the light-squared bishop will 
become active on b7.} ({The Semi-Slav becomes very sharp and concrete after} 5. 
Bg5 {and won't be covered here.})) ({• The third option, and our choice, is} 
4... dxc4 {. Black wants to develop his bishop to f5, but, as we know, it's not 
yet possible. Instead, Black first exploits the hanging c4-pawn. While White 
spends time regaining this pawn, Black has a chance to develop his light-squared 
bishop to f5. This is known as the Slav, or the Classical Slav (to differentiate 
it from the other Slav flavours). It will be the subject of this course.}) 5. a4 
{Before White tries to recoup the pawn, he must first eliminate any options 
Black has to support the c4-pawn. 5. a4 prevents ...b5 (which otherwise can give 
White some headaches).} ({Some minor white alternatives like} 5. Ne5 {,}) (5. 
e3) ({and} 5. g3 {sacrifice the pawn for good, but it usually turns out that 
white is short on compensation after} 5... b5 {.}) Bf5 6. Ne5 {[%cal 
Be5c4,Gf2f3,Ge2e4] Of the two main moves in this position - 6. Ne5 and 6. e3 - 
this is the most ambitious - as a result, it is also the top choice of the 
world's elite. White intends to regain the pawn on c4 with his knight. Note that 
this also frees up the f3-square - this means that White, if allowed, will play 
f3 followed by e4, claiming the whole centre for himself.} e6 {This is Black's 
second most-common choice. I think it's useful to just point out this 
crossroads.} 7. f3 {[%cal Be2e4]} Bb4 8. e4 Bxe4 9. fxe4 Nxe4 {[%cal 
Bd8h4,Gh4e1,Gb4c3,Ge4c3,Ge4g3,Gd8d4][%csl Rc3,Re1,Rd4]} 10. Bd2 Qxd4 11. Nxe4 
Qxe4+ 12. Qe2 Bxd2+ 13. Kxd2 Qd5+ 14. Kc2 Na6 15. Nxc4 $14 {After this long 
semi-forced variation we reach an interesting position where Black has 3 pawns 
for the piece. Based on recent games and analysis, it seems like White has the 
edge here.} *

