so as not to allow White to play the expanding f3 and e4.} 7. Nxc4 {White 
regains his pawn of course.} Nb6 {[%cal Gb6c4]} ({This will be my recommendation 
for Black. The main alternative is} 7... Qc7 {, which is often considered the 
mainline. I added one informational variation to show you how play can develop 
from 7... Qc7. I chose the move 7... Nb6, sometimes called the Sokolov 
variation, since I believe it is simple, strong and less theoretical than 7... 
Qc7.}) 8. Ne5 {White should of course avoid trading knights.} a5 {Secures the 
position of the knight on b6 by preventing White's 9. a5. From here, White has a 
number of methods of trying to develop:} ({• 1. He can try the ambitious} a5 
9. f3 {followed by e4.}) ({• 2. The simple} a5 9. e3 {option aims for quick 
development and castling.}) ({• 3. The recent choice of the elite (and the 
engine!) has been the interesting} a5 9. h4 $5 {.}) 9. f3 {[%cal Be2e4] This 
seems like one of White's most ambitious tries. He is making no attempt to hide 
the fact he wants to play 10. e4.} Nfd7 {[%cal Gd7e5][%csl Re5] Following the 
general rule of trading off pieces when you have less space, but the knight on 
e5 is also a particularly unpleasant piece.} 10. Nxd7 Nxd7 11. e4 Bg6 12. Be2 e6 
13. O-O Bb4 $11 {[%cal Be8g8,Ge6e5][%csl Bb4] The position is pretty much 
balanced. White has some extra space, but Black has a very compact pawn 
structure with no real weaknesses in addition to his important b4 outpost. The 
usual plans of a central break at some point applies here, although ...c5 
weakens b5 so ...e5 would usually be the one Black prepares in this position.} *

